, and the causes of war. Lieber's cases explore the military and political implications of the spread of railroads, the emergence of rifled small arms and artillery, the introduction of battle tanks, and the nuclear revolution. Lieber incorporates the new historiography of World War I, which draws on archival materials that only recently became available, to challenge many common beliefs about the conflict. The author's central conclusion is that technology is neither a cause of international conflict nor a panacea; instead, power politics remains paramount.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMilitary art and sciencexPolitical aspectsvCase studies. 0aMilitary art and sciencexTechnological innovationsxHistoryy19th centuryvCase studies. 0aMilitary art and sciencexTechnological innovationsxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aMilitary weaponsxHistoryy19th centuryvCase studies. 0aMilitary weaponsxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aSecurity, InternationalxHistoryy19th centuryvCase studies. 0aSecurity, InternationalxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 4aMilitary History. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSecurity Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172446640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501724466423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501724466/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles